<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1866-04-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1866-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="325" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Speed</persName>,
                                    Attorney-General, to Mr. <persName type="to">Kelby</persName>,
                                    district, attorney.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <dateline><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Office of the
                                        Attorney-General</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1866-04-21"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 21,
                                1866</date>.</dateline>
                            <p><seg type="margin">[9]</seg> *<hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I
                                inclose to you a copy of a letter this day received by me from the
                                Secretary of State.</p>
                            <p>You will be on the watch, and careful to see that the neutrality law
                                is not violated.</p>
                            <p>Very respectfully, &amp;c.,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>JAMES SPEED,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Attorney-General.</hi></signed>
                            </closer>
                            <postscript>
                                <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Hiram Kelby</hi>, Esq.,<lb/><hi rend="italic">United States Attorney, New London,
                                        Connecticut.</hi></p>
                            </postscript>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>